  "eprint": {
    "title": "Fully Collision-Resistant Chameleon-Hashes from Simpler and Post-Quantum Assumptions",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "David Derler",
        "email": "david@dfinity",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Stephan Krenn",
        "email": "krenn@ait",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Kai Samelin",
        "email": "atkaispapers@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Daniel Slamanig",
        "email": "slamanig@ait",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Chameleon-hashes are collision-resistant hash-functions parametrized\nby a public key. If the corresponding secret key is known, arbitrary collisions for the hash can be found.\nRecently, Derler et al. (PKC '20) introduced the notion of fully collision-resistant chameleon-hashes.\nFull collision-resistance requires the intractability of finding collisions,\neven with full-adaptive access to a collision-finding oracle. Their construction combines simulation-sound extractable (SSE)\nNIZKs with perfectly correct IND-CPA secure public-key encryption (PKE) schemes.\n\nWe show that, instead of perfectly correct PKE, non-interactive commitment schemes are sufficient. For the first time, this gives rise to efficient instantiations from plausible post-quantum assumptions and thus candidates of chameleon-hashes with strong collision-resistance guarantees and long-term security guarantees. On the more theoretical side, our results relax the requirement to not being dependent on public-key encryption.",
    "keywords": [
      "Chameleon-hash"
    ],
    "category": "Secret-key cryptography",
    "publication_info": "Published elsewhere. Major revision. SCN 2020",
